The Women&rsquo;s Law Student Association (WLSA) promotes the advancement of women and non-binary people in the legal profession. WLSA sponsors panel discussions and lunch lectures on Women's issues, social events, and professional development opportunities.&nbsp;
WLSA annually hosts a fundraiser event with the Public Interest Law Foundation (PILF) to raise money for scholarships for women attending UW-Law.&nbsp;
WLSA's overall Mission is to support women and non-binary people at the University of Wisconsin-Law School.

Our mission, at the Women's Pre-Law Association (WPLA) is to empower and support women aspiring to enter the legal profession by providing resources, mentorship, and networking opportunities. We strive to foster a supportive community of women, promoting academic excellence and professional growth, to address the underrepresentation of women in the legal field.
&nbsp;
The Women&rsquo;s Pre-Law Association organizes events such as panel discussions with women in various areas of law, LSAT preparation and law school application workshops, and member bonding activities. These programs are designed to provide both practical guidance and a sense of community for women pursuing legal careers.
&nbsp;
More information can be found on our Instagram, LinkedIn, and in our organizational emails. If you wish to be added to our email list, you can sign up through this Google Form.

The Wisconsin Union Directorate Cuisine Committee provides education about food transparency, sustainability, and justice and encourages the community to explore its impact on Wisconsin's food system.
Through educational events, meeting speakers, field trips, and cooking demonstrations and tastings, the Cuisine Committee strives to provide programming that services and reflects the diverse, multicultural backgrounds of the student population and provides context to thinking through issues surrounding food systems.
Another exciting offering from WUD Cuisine is cooking workshops, giving students the skills to cook great meals within a student's budget.&nbsp;

YesUW is based on the principles of the YouTube Channel&nbsp;Yes Theory&nbsp;and the process of&nbsp; seeking discomfort. We believe that the key to forming deeper connections and creating more fulfilling experiences require stepping outside our comfort zones. By going outside our comfort zones, we can see new perspectives and shake us out of our daily lives. Doing so reminds&nbsp; us that our day to day routine isn&rsquo;t the only thing that is out there. As&nbsp;Yes Theory&nbsp;says, &ldquo;Break out of your routine, and you&rsquo;ll find new creative energy.&rdquo; These change-ups allow us to see the world in a new light and can inspire new ideas. The only issue with trying new experiences is that they can be uncomfortable. We sit in our day to day lives thinking&nbsp;why go out and try something new, that seems like so much work.&nbsp;It's easy to find a million reasons to say&nbsp;no, it&rsquo;s hard to say&nbsp;yes.
&nbsp;
And yet, we find ourselves bored with that day to day life. To find fulfillment, we have to go outside our comfort zones. We want to be the facilitator for these experiences so that&nbsp; everyone who is inspired will be able to seek discomfort and fulfillment on a regular basis.
